{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510588"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:32:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:32:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11614"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11614"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.18,0.01,0.39,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4241"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79127"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4241"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11614"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64479"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1509"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5607"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7185"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26978"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79127","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79127"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man is referred to a nephrologist regarding persistent microscopic haematuria detected on a urine dipstick. He describes himself as very healthy and denies any recent infections or illnesses. Family history is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExamination yields no abnormalities. Urine dipstick reveals the presence of microscopic haematuria and absence of proteinuria. Urine microscopy confirms haematuria with dysmorphic red cells. A kidney biopsy was performed, there were no abnormalities detected on light microscopy, and electron microscopy showed diffuse thinning of the glomerular basement membrane.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Given these findings, which one of the following is the most appropriate management option?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No active management required","Angiotensin-converting-enzyme inhibitor","Diuretic","Prednisolone","Hemodialysis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThese findings are consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Ethin basement membrane nephropathy\u003C/strong\u003E (TBMN, also known as benign familial haematuria).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt present, evidence-based guidelines \u003Cstrong\u003Edo not recommend any management\u003C/strong\u003E for patients with TBMN, as the prognosis is usually excellent. A degree of renal impairment is present in around 7% of people with TBMN, however, it often results from coincidental superimposed glomerulonephritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is recommended that only patients with proteinuria\u0026gt;500\u00a0mg/day, hypertension, or renal impairment may benefit from \u003Cstrong\u003Eangiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor therapy.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiuretics\u003C/strong\u003E should only be considered in the presence of edema and/or severe hypertension after the trial of an ACE inhibitor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone \u003C/strong\u003Eis only indicated for use in a nephritic syndrome where membranoproliferative disease is present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDialysis\u003C/strong\u003E should not be considered unless end-stage renal failure is present, or as determined by a nephrologist.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thin basement membrane nephropathy does not require any active management.","Microscopic haematuria with dysmorphic red cells and thin glomerular basement membrane on electron microscopy suggests thin basement membrane nephropathy."],"references":["Savige J, Rana K, Tonna S, Buzza M, Dagher H, Wang YY. Thin basement membrane nephropathy. Kidney Int. 2003 Oct;64(4):1169-78. doi: 10.1046/j.1523-1755.2003.00234.x. PMID: 12969134. Available from:","Kashtan CE. Thin basement membrane nephropathy (benign familial haematuria). Up to date. Updated August 12, 2021. Accessed September 23, 2022. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/thin-basement-membrane-nephropathy-benign-familial-hematuria?search=thin%20basement%20membrane%20sydnrome\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1~76\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1#H14Thin%20basement%20membrane%20nephropathy","Ramakrishnan M, Leslie SW. Thin Basement Membrane Nephropathy. [Updated 2024 Aug 31]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK594234/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64479"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11614"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64479"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T15:21:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T15:21:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4241"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79127"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","li